Unemployment in South Africa is rife and is cause for concern. If the president doesn’t deal with it, we’re not going anywhere as a country. Unemployment is going to result in chaos. We must bear in mind that the high unemployment rate is one of the causes of xenophobia and crime in Mzansi. South African youth are always at the forefront of xenophobic attacks and dangerous crime. There’s nothing as painful as studying for about seven years at university, hoping to get a job after graduating, only to end up staying at home for more than 10 years, unemployed. The unemployment rate continues to be felt by those who’re financially oppressed but favours the financially secure and politically connected. Ramaphosa must come up with solutions for both the private and public sectors to create jobs Letter by Miyelani Hlungwani from Mukhomi Village